The function of PROJECT is to handle file management. This includes saving, loading of text and graphics and printing of the document. Each command is described below.


PROJECT
       New       (A) N

       This command erase any document you have open and starts over with a blank screen. By selecting this option using the mouse or by holding down the right (A)miga key and pressing the "N" key, all items are erased from memory. This is the "start from scratch" option.


PROJECT
       Open...   (A) O

       This option opens projects that have been stored under C‚i‚t‚y‚ ‚D‚e‚s‚k‚.  Selecting this option brings up the same requester as Load Text or Load graphics. This command is also activated by holding down the right (A)miga key and pressing the letter "O" at the same time.


PROJECT
       Save

       This option stores files using the same filename that they were loaded with. The new copy replaces the old project. If you started a project without a title use the "SAVE AS..." option to assign a name.


PROJECT
       Save As... (A) S

       Save As... prompts you to enter a project title when storing a new project. This option is also useful for saving more that one copy of a document.  This command is also activated by holding down the right (A)miga key and pressing the letter "S" at the same time.


PROJECT
       Load Text   (A) T

       This requester displays the list of files stored in the current drive and directory. If you need to change drives or directories, click the drawer gadget and enter the new drive or directory name. 
   The slider located on the right side of the list of files moves up or down this list of filenames. 
   To load a text file, point to the filename and click the left mouse button. The "OK" gadget submits the file to C‚i‚t‚y‚ ‚D‚e‚s‚k‚. 
   C‚i‚t‚y‚ ‚D‚e‚s‚k‚ supplies you with sample articles.

PROJECT
       Load Graphic  (A) G

       This requester is similar to the "LOAD TEXT" option, but instead of loading text files it loads graphics stored in IFF format.
  C‚i‚t‚y‚ ‚D‚e‚s‚k‚ provides you with a library of clip art work. Change the directory name to "CLIP ART" for a listing of picture filenames.


PROJECT
       Save Object...

       This option stores on disk a single graphic or text object that has been loaded on C‚i‚t‚y‚ ‚D‚e‚s‚k‚. The requester "Save Object" prompts you to enter a filename to save this object.


PROJECT
       Print        (A) P

       This option prints a hardcopy of the current page to the printer. It does not print the entire document. "PRINT" may also be activated by pressing the right (A)miga key and the letter "P" at the same time.


PROJECT
       Print Document

       This option prints the entire document.


PROJECT
       ABOUT  

       This option provides information about C‚i‚t‚y‚ ‚D‚e‚s‚k‚ and its authors.


PROJECT
       QUIT     (A) Q

       The QUIT option exits C‚i‚t‚y‚ ‚D‚e‚s‚k‚ and returns to AmigaDOS. Before exiting, C‚i‚t‚y‚ ‚D‚e‚s‚k‚ gives a friendly reminder to make sure that you are ready to quit and that your work is saved. Click the "OK" gadget if you are ready, otherwise click the "CANCEL" gadget.
       Pressing the right (A)miga key and the letter "Q" at the same time also activates the QUIT option.



The EDIT menu
@Use Mini Editor@(A) E
@Edit Text Attributes@(A) A
@Edit Page Format@(A) F
@Reflow Text Chain@(A) R
@Invert Graphic@(A) I

The function of the EDIT menu is to edit text, text attributes, or page format. Also included in this menu is a special option for inverting and editing graphics.


EDIT
    Use Mini Editor    (A) E

    C‚i‚t‚y‚ ‚D‚e‚s‚k‚ provides you with some editing capabilities. When you select this option, the mouse pointer prompts you to PICK the object to be edited. You may pick a block of  text or a graphic. If you pick a block of text, this block appears as one long line in the edit mode. An example of the Mini editor is shown below.


     PICTURE


The slider located along the bottom of this line allows to move right or left on the text line. You may also use the right and left arrow keys to position the cursor along this line.

Editing in this mode consists of deleting, inserting, and searching of characters. Use the DEL key or backspace key to delete  characters. Use right-Amiga X to delete everything. Inserting a character or a word is automatic.

Searching for a string is done by entering the string to look for 
in the bottom string gadget and then clicking << or >>. >> will search forward, and << will search backwards.

To save the corrections click the "OK" gadget. The "CANCEL" gadget ignores all corrections.

   If you pick a graphic to edit, you will enter the Graphics Editor. For a complete explanation of each menu in this editor, please see the "Graphics Editor Menus" in a later section of this manual.


EDIT
    Edit Text Attributes     (A) A

    This option controls the current appearance of text. Items in this menu include changing the current font, font size, spacing between lines,  magnification, space stretch and some other attributes.  This option prompts you to PICK the block of text to be altered.

To change the defaults for all new text, use the right mouse button on the ABC tool.

    A summary of the items in the "Edit Text Attributes" option follows:

  Justification: Types of justification in this requester are abbreviated as follows:
    L  (left justification
    R  (right justification)
    C  (center justification)
    F  (fill justification}
   The default is Fill justification

   Attributes or typestyles in this window are abbreviated as:
    C  compressed. Valid on HP laser fonts only.
    B  boldface 
    U  underlined
    I  italic.
    You may use one or any combination of the above. The default is no attribute (plain text.)

    Spacing: This indicates the vertical distance from the the bottom of one line to the top of the next line. This is different  
from leading, which can only be set by using an escape command within the text.

    Space Stretch: In fill justify, this is the distance between words at which City Desk will start putting spaces between letter.  To fill a line, City Desk normally puts space between words up to the "Space Stretch" limit.  After this point is reached, spaces will be put between words and the letters in the words. This is called "micro Justification" by some desktop publishing packages.

Font Name: Changes the font name. The default font is TOPAZ.
Font Size: Displays the font size. The default size is 8.

 NEWFONT:   This gadget pops up the "Select A Font" requester. Choose the font type (Amiga, or Laser.) Select the desired font and font size. The "-" and "+" gadgets on this requester move up or down the list of fonts and font sizes for the appropriate printer.

When a font is displayed, you will also be shown which attributes are available for that font (on laser printers, not all attributes are available for all fonts, except underlined, which is always available.) "B" means bold, "I" means italic, and "bi" means bold-italic.

Click the "OK" gadget to submit the new font name and size. The "CANCEL" box ignores all corrections.

Horizontal Mag: Horizontal magnification of characters. When magnifying horizontally, the characters appear to be stretched out or squeezed. Default horizontal magnification size is 1. This command affects the entire block of text. Some sample magnifications would be .5, 1, 2.5, 8.


   Vertical Mag: Vertical magnification of characters. This option has the effect of enlarging or shrinking characters in the vertical direction.  This option is useful when font sizes do not have the desired large or small letters.  Vertical magnification is only valid for Amiga fonts, not laser fonts. The default size is 1. Magnifying in this mode affects an entire block of text.

NOTE: At the time of this writing, magnification only works on AMIGA fonts (topaz, ruby, sapphire, etc.) and is planned for PostScript. It may or may not be working on PostScript at the release date.


EDIT

