This menu includes many functions. These functions include display information about printer  or page settings. Each of these options is described below.


PREFERENCES
           Save...

           Preferences' Save... stores to disk any changes made to the default text format or the default page format from the ABC or the OPEN_PAGE tools so that they will be available for future sessions. Saving these formats under the filename "AUTOPREFS" will cause C‚i‚t‚y‚ ‚D‚e‚s‚k‚ to automatically load these defaults each time you run the program.


PREFERENCES
           Load...

           Preferences' Load... loads the default text or page format stored in previous sessions.


PREFERENCES
           Print Options

          This brings up the "Print Options" requester. With this requester, you can enter the page number to start numbering  with, banners for the odd or even pages, whether to print to a file or the printer, and the font to use for page numbers.


PREFERENCES
           Display Resolution     640 x 200
                                  640 x 400

          This option lets you select whether or not to use interlaced mode for the screen display. Interlaced (640 X 400) is NOT recommended without external RAM (1 MEG total RAM or more). The default display resolution is 640 x 200 lines.


PREFERENCES
           Column Guides are      Visible
                                  Invisible

           Column Guides (for text formatting purposes) may be or may not be displayed on the working page window. These guides are shown as dash lines and are not printed on paper. The default is to have the column guides visible.


PREFERENCES
           Print To              Preferences
                                 HP LaserJet
                                 Postscript

           Before you start placing text or graphics on the page you must make sure you let C‚i‚t‚y‚ ‚D‚e‚s‚k‚ know the type of printer you own. Three types of printer drivers are available: Amiga Preferences, HP LaserJet or compatible and  PostScript. The default printer option is Amiga Preferences. Once you create a document on one type of printer, it will not appear the same on a different printer. This is because C‚i‚t‚y‚ ‚D‚e‚s‚k‚ adjust font sizes to look the best on your printer. You CANNOT change printer types in the middle of creating a document.


PREFERENCES
           LaserJet Resolution    75 dpi
                                 100 dpi
                                 150 dpi
                                 300 dpi

           Default printer resolution for HP LaserJet printers is selected from this option. Resolution is given in terms of dpi (dots per inch.) There are four resolution options: 75, 100, 150 or 300 dpi. The higher the number, the better the print quality but the more memory is used in the LaserJet. The default is 75 dpi. This option only has an effect if you are using an HP LaserJet or compatible.


PREFERENCES
           Show Printer Info

           This option displays a window showing the printer name and  the X and Y printer resolution in dots per inch (dpi) of the printer you have selected with AMIGA preferences (not the same as City Desk preferences).


PREFERENCES
           Paragraph End     1 Return
                             2 Returns

           This option sets the number of carriage returns at the end of a paragraph in any text file. The default is to have one carriage return.


PREFERENCES
           Strip Spaces      On
                             Off

           When loading text files, you may have the option of suppressing the extra spaces in the file. Therefore the effect is to have a single blank between each word in a line. The default is not to strip spaces.


PREFERENCES
           Load File Type    Amiga
                             ASCII
                             Scribble!

           This option must be set before you load a text file. It is very important to determine the type of file being loaded for proper text formatting. Three options are available: Amiga (when you use ED or EDIT), ASCII, and Scribble! files. The default is to load Amiga files.



GRID
@Grid Snap is@
@Grid Display is@
@Grid Spacing is@

The grid provides even spacing between blocks of text, lines of text or figures. All text and figure corners are forced to be placed against a grid dot when the grid snap is on.


GRID
    Grid Snap is   On
                   Off

    This option turns on or off the grid snap. When grid snap is on, all text blocks and figure corners are forced to be placed against a grid dot to achieve even spacing between objects. The default is grid snap off.


GRID
    Grid Display is   On
                      Off

    This choice turns on or off the grid display.  Grid dots are placed at regular intervals from each other. These dots are not printed to your printer - they are only displayed on the screen. This distance is controlled in the "Grid Spacing Is" option.


GRID
    Grid Spacing is     1 pt
                        6 pt
                        12 pt = 1 pica
                        18 pt = 0.25 in
                        36 pt = 0.50 in
                        Any Other

    Grid spacing determines the distance between one grid dot and the next. This option is used in conjunction with Grid snap on. The default grid dot spacing is 36 points (or 0.5 inches). You may assign any other grid spacing using any valid unit of measure.



TOOLBOX
@To Front@(A) \]
@To Back@(A) \[

       These functions are similar to the window depth arrangement gadgets. They control whether the toolbox is displayed or not.


TOOLBOX
       To Front  (A) \]

       This option puts the toolbox on top of all other windows. This command is also activated by pressing the right (A)miga key and the close bracket key at the same time.


TOOLBOX
       To Back  (A) \[

       This command hides the toolbox behind all other windows. You may also activate this option by pressing the right (A)miga key and the open bracket key at the same time.



FLOW OPTIONS
@Snap to Top@
@Auto Flow@

   This menu controls automatic flowing and the position of the text when a page or column becomes full.


FLOW OPTIONS
            Snap to Top   On
                          Off

            This option places text at the top of the next column or at the top of the next page when a page or column becomes full of text. The default is off.


FLOW OPTIONS
            Auto Flow     On
                          Off

            When a column or page becomes full with text, "Auto Flow" On will automatically flow text onto the next column or page. Note that you must open the next page to see the remaining of the text. The default is Auto Flow off.
             